 Selva, Costa Rica", "series": "Journal of Geophysical Research", "edition": "", "volume": "115", "issue": "", "publication_place": "", "publisher": "", "pages": "", "isbn": "", "year": "2010"}]}', '{"citation": "incomplete", "contacts": "incomplete", "introduction": "incomplete", "historical_perspective": "incomplete", "scientific_theory": "incomplete", "mathematical_theory": "incomplete", "input_variables": "incomplete", "output_variables": "incomplete", "constraints": "incomplete", "validation": "incomplete", "discussion": "incomplete", "acknowledgements": "incomplete", "abstract": "incomplete", "publication_checklist": "incomplete", "context_background": "incomplete", "version_description": "incomplete"}', NULL, NULL, 'ce55b12c-b868-4e37-b045-1777028d92e6', '2021-07-08 19:46:49.43313+00', '163c12ec-cda6-4a71-b576-25e59a372a86', '2022-01-13 00:22:46.193651+00', '', '{"creators": "hao tang", "editors": "", "title": "", "series_name": "", "release_date": "", "release_place": "", "publisher": "", "version": "", "issue": "", "additional_details": "", "online_resource": ""}', '163c12ec-cda6-4a71-b576-25e59a372a86', '{ce55b12c-b868-4e37-b045-1777028d92e6}', '{}', 'DRAFT', 'PUBLICATION_INTENDED', '{"suggested_reviewers": [{"name": "Felix Morsdorf", "email": "felix.morsdorf@geo.uzh.ch"}, {"name": "Philip Lewis", "email": "philip.lewis@ucl.ac.uk"}, {"name": "Crystal Schaaf", "email": "crystal.schaaf@umb.edu"}], "review_roles": true, "journal_editor": "Chelle Gentemann", "author_affirmations": true}', '{}');
INSERT INTO apt.atbd_versions (major, minor, atbd_id, document, sections_completed, published_by, published_at, created_by, created_at, last_updated_by, last_updated_at, doi, citation, owner, authors, reviewers, status, journal_status, publication_checklist, keywords) VALUES (1, 0, 3, '{"abstract": null, "introduction": {"children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The Global Ecosystem Dynamics Investigation (GEDI) is producing measurements of vertical forest structure using a multibeam waveform lidar on the International Space Station ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "95dd42c5", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Two objectives of the mission are to quantify the distribution of aboveground carbon in woody vegetation, and to use these estimates to determine the impact of land use and land-cover changes on aboveground carbon stocks. Both of these objectives speak to fundamental uncertainties in our understanding of the role of the land surface in the global carbon cycle ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "6fda62c4", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9646918a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The sole GEDI observable is the received laser waveform ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "95dd42c5", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The waveform represents the vertical distribution of intercepted surfaces within the extent of the illuminated laser footprint, and is available as the GEDI level-1B (GEDI01_B) data product ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "04545783", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Estimating aboveground biomass density (AGBD) using GEDI data requires algorithms that process GEDI01_B waveforms to quantify relative height (RH) metrics. RH metrics define the percentage of the received laser waveform intensity that is less than a given height, where height is computed relative to the elevation of the lowest mode in the waveform. RH metrics are estimated in the presence of measurement uncertainty, including varying atmospheric conditions and solar background radiation. This uncertainty propagates through GEDI level-2A (GEDI02_A) RH metrics that are used to predict AGBD ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "594f393d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The first release of the GEDI level-4A (GEDI04_A) data product is based on Version 1 of GEDI02_A ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "594f393d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), and uses one of six algorithm setting groups to interpret the received waveform and identify the elevation of the lowest mode ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "da19e90e", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The Version 1 of GEDI04_A uses linear statistical models selected from an ensemble of candidates that predict AGBD as a function of one or more RH metrics. GEDI04_A models are a required input to the 1 km GEDI level-4B (GEDI04_B) AGBD data product ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "207bf081", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}]}, "data_availability": null, "scientific_theory": {"children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "All remote sensing estimates of AGBD rely on field measurements of individual tree structure ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "b1166bee", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "7387a24f", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The mass of a given individual tree, "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ",", "subscript": true}, {"text": " is derived using allometric-scaling models developed from destructive harvesting and weighing of trees. In their most general form, these models assume that "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " is a power function of trunk diameter, "}, {"text": "X", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ":"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "M_i \\: \\alpha \\:aX_{i}^{b}"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Numerous investigations including hundreds of species have demonstrated that M_i is a power function of tree size under a wide range of conditions ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "859ca402", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "30660e72", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "e5b19dda", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9227a11d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "20d75c3a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1415ce35", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "172af1ce", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ab059b12", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "734a16f4", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "0b94e395", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "In practice, the variable indicated by "}, {"text": "X", "italic": true}, {"text": "i ", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": "is usually the diameter of the stem at breast height (DBH), defined as 1.3 m. Some models use tree height in addition to DBH, and others incorporate wood specific gravity, defined as oven-dried mass divided by wet volume ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "0eb96dfe", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Because it is not always possible to weigh an entire tree, wood samples are heated in an oven until mass stabilizes. The oven-dry mass per unit wet volume is computed from the samples, and measurements of DBH and height are used to compute total wood volume. Wood volume is multiplied by wood specific gravity to obtain "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ". Repeating this process for many individual trees results in data that are used to estimate the parameters of equation (3)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "For every tree-record in the FSBD we used an allometric model appropriate to the given PFT and world region to predict For every tree-record in the FSBD we used an allometric model appropriate to the given PFT and world region to predict "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ". When there was more than one model that could be used for a given tree, we favored locally developed models over regional ones, as long as locally-developed models were not site-specific. We also favored models with finer taxonomic resolution. In Australia we use eight allometric models developed by "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ab059b12", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " and "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "734a16f4", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ". In New Zealand we use the model developed by "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1415ce35", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " for "}, {"text": "Pinus radiata", "italic": true}, {"text": ", and the model of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "859ca402", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " for all other species. In North America we use the models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "20d75c3a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " in the continental United States and the models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "0b94e395", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " in Canada. In Europe we use the allometric models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9227a11d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ". Throughout the tropics of South America, Africa and Asia we use the model of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "e5b19dda", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "In some situations there was more than one candidate model to predict "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " that met GEDI04_A requirements. For example, the models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "30660e72", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " and "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "e5b19dda", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " have been used to predict "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": "  in Central American evergreen broadleaf forests. The models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "172af1ce", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " and "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9227a11d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " have been used in deciduous broadleaf and evergreen needleleaf forests of Europe. The models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "20d75c3a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " and the component ratio method (CRM; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "85815942", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ") have been used in North American forests of the United States of America. There is evidence that the CRM underestimates AGBD, especially in deciduous broadleaf forests of the eastern United States ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "335cba16", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9ee63877", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). However, the CRM produces values that are greater than "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "20d75c3a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " in forests taller than 50 m. Choosing a model to predict "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": "  is important and has resulted in large discrepancies in estimates of AGBD from spaceborne remote sensing ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "6ec34cd0", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Studies are needed that compare predictions of "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": "  to harvested trees that have been dried and weighed to determine which allometric models have the best performance. Subsequent versions of GEDI04_A may use different allometric models. "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Some contributed data records for individual trees included measurements of height and diameter, but some measurements only contained diameter. When the allometric model required height as an input and a measured value was available, we used the measured value. When no height measurement was available we predicted height in one of three ways. If some records contained estimates of height and diameter, we developed a local height-diameter relationship using complete data records. If no height measurements were available, we used the published height-diameter allometry of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "172af1ce", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " in Europe and the models of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "80076a80", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " elsewhere except the United States. In the United States, we developed a local height-diameter allometry using United States Department of Agriculture Forest Inventory and Analysis (FIA) data within the same county. We then applied this locally developed model to predict tree height."}]}]}, "journal_discussion": {"children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "GEDI04_A models were developed using methods that evaluate performance outside the geographic extent of training data, a problem we call geographic transferability. These models were trained using simulated GEDI waveforms in the absence of sensor noise. There are three priority areas where improvement in GEDI04_A models is likely to be realized. "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "8.1 Improved representation of training data"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Although the GEDI FSBD is comprehensive, it is a post hoc collocation of community contributed data that was filtered by a series of quality control checks. This resulted in 24 out of 35 prediction strata where we were unable to develop or test a candidate model, including many important stratifications with substantial aboveground carbon density ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "d0f1d3d3", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). These strata represent all of North Asia, the dry savannas and woodlands of South America and South Asia, and GSW strata worldwide. Even within strata that are more densely sampled, data used for model training may not be representative of relationships between RH metrics and AGBD throughout the prediction stratum. For example, training data in the EBT  Australia and Oceania world region are from two projects in the Australian state of Queensland. However, this prediction stratum also includes the Island of New Guinea, and other islands of the Malay Archipelago east of the Wallace line. The degree to which existing training data are representative an entire prediction stratum underpins the veracity of GEDI04_A. Two important priorities are documenting representativeness of training data within prediction strata, and filling data gaps. Both of these actions can also support the activities of other current and forthcoming space missions, including ICESat-2, NISAR and ESA BIOMASS ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1db3e9f6", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ", "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9888a043", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "88d81cc0", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "b608d502", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "e5ea1cc6", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Training data must also be representative of GEDI waveform properties. The release 1 GEDI04_A models were developed using simulated noiseless waveforms, where ground elevation was known exactly from discrete-return ALS. In practice, identifying the ground-return in recorded GEDI data can be challenging under conditions of dense canopy cover and complex terrain. The GEDI02_A data product includes results for seven algorithm setting groups to interpret the received waveform and identify the signal start, end, and elevation of the lowest mode ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "da19e90e", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The elevation of the lowest mode is treated as ground elevation. Ground-finding errors will propagate through RH metrics and impact AGBD predictions developed in the absence of these errors. GEDI waveform signal-to-noise is also impacted by time of day (due to the solar background illumination) and laser power (power versus coverage beams). Documenting transferability of GEDI04_A models from simulated noiseless to recorded GEDI waveforms with measurement artifacts and ground-finding errors is a research priority. In addition, new GEDI04_A models will be updated using simulated waveform data parameterized with on-orbit measurements of the GEDI transmitted pulse and noise. "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "8.2 Strengthening allometric models"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "All remote sensing of AGBD depends on field measurements of individual trees ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "b1166bee", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The quality of AGBD data products from remote sensing therefore depends on the accuracy of field estimates and the degree to which field estimates are representative of relationships between AGBD and remote sensing data. Because direct measurement of standing aboveground biomass is not possible in the absence of harvesting, estimates of AGBD are derived from allometric models. These models relate measurements of tree structure  typically stem diameter and tree height  to AGBD using relationships developed from trees that have been harvested, dried and weighed. Recent work has called into question the assumption that scaling equations generate unbiased estimates of individual tree mass. Harvested trees used to develop allometric models are typically small in size and have not been randomly sampled. One recent study using harvested trees demonstrated that M_i is underestimated for large trees by allometric models (e.g., "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "3dd72ff3", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). An important area for future research is the development of improved allometric models or alternative methods based on terrestrial laser scanning or drone lidar ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "fdf7db74", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ed685cd4", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "66874461", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1db3e9f6", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "d488d14b", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "25acc21c", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "8.3 Application of machine learning to AGBD prediction"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "\tThe hybrid-inference framework selected for GEDI04_B requires footprint models that are linear and parametric, from which a covariance matrix that describes relationships among model parameters can be derived. This covariance matrix enables a closed-form estimate of uncertainty when GEDI04_A predictions are aggregated to large areas (e.g., the 1 km GEDI04_B grid, or other arbitrary regions; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "207bf081", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "01c7ba43", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). This requirement ruled out non-parametric methods and approaches based on non-linear machine learning in the development of GEDI04_A models (e.g., ensemble-based decision trees and neural networks; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "2f7027bb", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Whether alternative specifications based on machine learning can improve the quality of GEDI04_A predictions is not known. However, reducing uncertainty in GEDI04_A independent of GEDI04_B would improve the standalone GEDI04_A data product and support investigations that require footprint-level resolution. This includes integration of footprint AGBD with Landsat forest cover loss ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "83e37f0d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), fusion of GEDI04_A with TanDEM-X to produce gridded AGBD at a finer resolution than the 1 km GEDI04_B data product ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "37f71440", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ") , and simulations from prognostic ecosystem model outputs ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "09a6a557", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ae02842c", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), all of which are GEDI demonstrative products that require footprint AGBD. It may also be possible to use machine learning to engineer features that are linearly related to footprint AGBD. If successful, this could facilitate increased predictive power from machine learning in a way that is compliant with GEDI04_B algorithms"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}]}, "mathematical_theory": {"children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Because "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " ", "subscript": true}, {"text": "is modeled as a power function of stem diameter and height, model functional forms that linearize the relationship between AGBD and RH metrics and minimize heteroskedasticity are necessary. GEDI04_A considers four functional forms: (i) a square-root transformation on the response, (ii) a square-root transformation on the response and predictors, (iii) a natural logarithm transformation on the response, and (iv) a natural logarithm transformation on the response and predictors ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "5a98b7c7", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Back-transforming model predictions from the square-root or natural logarithm scale requires a back-transformation bias correction. For models using the natural logarithm transformation, we considered two bias corrections. The method originally developed by "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "be28bddb", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " transforms values from the natural logarithm scale to the original scale using:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "\\overline{AGBD}_{i,j} = exp \\Big( \\bm {X}_i \\bm \\beta_j + \\frac {\\frac {1}{n} \\sum\\ _{i=1}^n (log(AGDB_i)- \\bm X_i \\bm \\beta_j)^2}{2} \\Big)"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The term $x^2$ denotes predicted values for footprint "}, {"text": "i", "italic": true}, {"text": " model "}, {"text": "j", "italic": true}, {"text": " in natural logarithm units using matrix notation, where "}, {"bold": true, "text": "[equation variable]"}, {"text": " is a row vector of predictor variables including a 1 for the intercept and ["}, {"bold": true, "text": "equation variable"}, {"text": "] is column vector of coefficients. {AGBD}"}, {"text": "i", "subscript": true}, {"text": " is the natural logarithm of AGBD from field data within the simulated GEDI footprint."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "7b516e45", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": " developed a ratio estimator for bias correction that is less sensitive to violations of the assumptions of logarithmic normality. The back-transformed value is:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "\\overline{AGBD}_{i,j} = C_j \\times exp( \\bm {X}_i \\bm \\beta_j)"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "C", "italic": true}, {"text": "j ", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " is a bias-correction coefficient:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "C_j = \\frac {\\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n}AGBD_i}{\\frac {1}{n} \\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n} exp (\\bm X_i \\bm \\beta_j)}"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "For models with a square-root transformation on the response, we used the bias-correction of "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "7b516e45", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ", where the bias-correction coefficient is: "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "C_j = \\frac {\\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n}AGBD_i}{\\frac {1}{n} \\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n} \\bm X_i \\bm \\beta_j^2}"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The back-transformed value for models with a square-root transformation on the response is:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "\\overline{AGBD}_{i,j} = C_j \\times exp( \\bm {X}_i \\bm \\beta_j)^2"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "We provide prediction intervals and estimates of the standard error of the prediction for every predicted value of AGBD. The standard error of the prediction for GEDI footprint "}, {"text": "h", "italic": true}, {"text": " is:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "SE_h = \\sqrt {MSE_k + \\bm X_h Cov(\\bm \\beta)\\bm X _{h}^{T}}"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Here, "}, {"text": "MSE", "italic": true}, {"text": "k", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " ", "subscript": true}, {"text": "is the square of the residual standard error from the linear regression applied to prediction stratum "}, {"text": "k", "italic": true}, {"text": " containing GEDI footprint ["}, {"bold": true, "text": "equation variable"}, {"text": "] is the row vector of scaled and transformed RH metrics for GEDI footprint "}, {"text": "h", "italic": true}, {"text": ", and ["}, {"bold": true, "text": "equation variable"}, {"text": "] is the variance-covariance matrix for the model parameters in transformed units (i.e. natural-logarithm, square-root, or none)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Prediction intervals are calculated for every predicted value of AGBD according to:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "\\overline{AGBD}_h \\: \\pm t_{(1- \\frac {\\alpha}{2}, n-2)} \\: \\times SE_h"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The"}, {"text": " t", "italic": true}, {"text": " multiplier is the value from a "}, {"text": "t", "italic": true}, {"text": " distribution with confidence level ["}, {"bold": true, "text": "equation variable"}, {"text": "] and "}, {"text": "n-", "italic": true}, {"text": "2 degrees of freedom. Users can compute prediction intervals for arbitrary values of \\alpha using the degrees of freedom within the model_data group of the GEDI04_A product."}]}]}, "version_description": null, "additional_information": null, "data_access_input_data": null, "historical_perspective": {"children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Estimating AGBD using remote sensing requires aboveground biomass, "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ", for a sample of trees that has been computed using an allometric model in a fixed area, such as a field-inventory plot or lidar footprint. Summing the "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " over all individuals in the plot or footprint and expressing it per unit ground area produces an estimate of AGBD. Coincident remote sensing data are used to develop an empirical relationship between AGBD and a remotely sensed measurement. This relationship can then be used to predict AGBD using remotely sensed data ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ae033d7d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1a0b315a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Many remote sensing technologies have been used to quantify AGBD in forests, including passive optical sensors ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "112cbf78", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), Synthetic Aperture Radar systems ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "a4febc7e", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "f329dce1", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), discrete return airborne lidar ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9ab43f2d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "592e2cb9", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9b52e1b6", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), airborne waveform lidar systems ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ae033d7d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "65310eb2", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "497e7ac9", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "), and spaceborne waveform lidar ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "cae3a97c", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "5cc33fa7", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "1ec044cd", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Passive optical and SAR backscatter-based techniques typically saturate with increasing AGBD, with the degree of saturation depending on SAR wavelength ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "74b5529d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ccb75e73", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). Lidar consistently produces models with the best performance in comparison to other technologies ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "f329dce1", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "b8f9b513", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Most previous efforts have developed site-specific or regional relationships between AGBD and remote sensing measurements ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "b8f9b513", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). GEDI faces a different challenge: it needs to develop models and algorithms that perform well throughout the entire observation domain of the ISS. Locally developed or regional relationships between AGBD and height are unlikely to perform well at locations outside the limited geographic extent of training data unless procedures are developed specifically to ensure transferability beyond the extent of calibration measurements ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "acd64f33", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "c6e04712", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": ")"}]}, {"type": "sub-section", "children": [{"text": "Statistical model development"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Models to produce GEDI04_A were developed using field estimates of AGBD colocated with simulated GEDI waveforms derived from discrete-return airborne lidar ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "cbf9fe97", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "8f6ede97", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The justification for using simulated GEDI waveforms is that few locations on the land surface are associated with field estimates of AGBD that could be used to train GEDI models. Because GEDI is a sampling mission and most field plots are small, GEDI data will not intersect most of these locations during the mission life. The GEDI approach to developing footprint AGBD models considers multiple candidates stratified by world region and plant functional type (PFT; Fig. 1) with different functional forms."}]}, {"type": "image-block", "children": [{"type": "img", "children": [{"text": ""}], "objectKey": "8e0626-gedi_fig1.png"}, {"type": "caption", "children": [{"text": "Figure 1. Global stratification by five combinations of error-corrected and infilled MODIS MCD12Q1 V006 PFT (A) and world region (B) to produce GEDI04_A models. The box inset is the GEDI observation domain of 51.6 degrees N to S latitude. DBT (deciduous broadleaf trees), DNT (deciduous needleleaf trees), EBT (evergreen broadleaf trees), ENT (evergreen needleleaf trees), GSW (grasses, shrubs and woodlands). Af (Africa), Au (Australia and Oceania), Eu (Europe), N-Am (North America north of southern Mexico), N-As (North Asia), S-Am (South America, Central America, southern Mexico, and the Caribbean), S-As (South Asia)."}]}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "An important objective for GEDI04_A models is that they are transferable outside the domain of calibration. Two key components are geographic transferability, meaning that the models can be extrapolated to locations outside the geographic extent of training data, and transferability from simulated to recorded GEDI waveforms. Transferring models from simulated to recorded GEDI waveforms requires that the models are robust in the presence of errors and uncertainties, including measurement errors associated with the GEDI02_A algorithm for derivation of RH metrics ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "da19e90e", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "GEDI04_A models were developed using a quality-filtered calibration data set that contains simulated GEDI waveforms: the Forest Structure and Biomass Database (FSBD). This data set is one of the most exhaustive ever compiled for remote sensing of AGBD, but important regions are under-represented. These include the forests of continental Asia, the evergreen broadleaf forests throughout the islands of Southeast Asia and north of Australia, and the worldwide distribution of savannas and deciduous tropical forests (Table 1). To quantify geographic transferability, candidate models were evaluated within sets of 5-degree grid cells that contain simulated GEDI waveforms with coincident field data. This approach sets aside data from one grid cell for testing, and trains the model using data within the remaining grid cells. This model is used to predict AGBD within the held-out grid cell, and the process is repeated for all grid cells within each stratum for all models under consideration (Fig. 2)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "table-block", "children": [{"type": "table", "children": [{"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "DBT"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "DNT"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "EBT"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "ENT"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "GSW"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Total"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Africa"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "490"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "834"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "6"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "1,330"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Australia and Oceania"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "213"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "142"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "65"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "420"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Europe"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "333"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "417"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "750"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "North America"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "873"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "1,391"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "18"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "2,282"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "North Asia"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "2"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "36"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "38"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "South America"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3,441"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "3,441"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "South Asia"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "326"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "326"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tr", "children": [{"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Total"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "1,698"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "0"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "4,814"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "1,986"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "89"}]}]}, {"type": "td", "children": [{"type": "p", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "8,587"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "caption", "children": [{"text": "Table 1. Numbers of simulated GEDI waveforms used for footprint model development and testing. GEDI04_A models are stratified by combinations of world region and PFT derived from error-corrected and infilled MODIS data product MCD12Q1 V006. These are deciduous broadleaf trees (DBT; class 4), deciduous needleleaf trees (DNT; class 3), evergreen broadleaf trees (EBT, class 2), evergreen needleleaf trees (ENT, class 1), and grasses, shrubs and woodlands (GSW, classes 5, 6, and 11)."}]}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "image-block", "children": [{"type": "img", "children": [{"text": ""}], "objectKey": "bd7aac-gedi_fig2.png"}, {"type": "caption", "children": [{"text": "Figure 2. GEDI04_A algorithm flow. The GEDI04_A algorithm assimilates external data from GEDI02_A and other sources. A prediction is generated for every GEDI shot where algorithm_run_flag = 1. The algorithm looks up the GEDI04_A model using a world region grid and error-corrected and infilled MODIS MCD12Q1 PFT (Fig. 1). xvar is the transformed and scaled predictor data (GEDI02_A RH metrics). agbd and associated uncertainty are outputs of the GEDI04_A algorithm for every GEDI02_A algorithm selection setting. "}]}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.1 Stratification of GEDI04_A models"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Building globally representative GEDI04_A models requires stratification. The models are stratified by world region and PFT (Fig. 1, Table 1). World regions are the geologically defined continents of Africa and Europe. The South America world region is the continent of South America, Central America and the Caribbean islands, and geological North America south of southern Mexico. The Australia and Oceania world region is geological Australia and the island regions north of Australia on the east side of the Wallace line, which defines the floral and faunal boundary between Australia and Asia during the Pleistocene ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "163b055b", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). The islands of Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia are associated with the Australia and Oceania world region regardless of political affiliation. The North America world region includes geological North America north of southern Mexico. We divide the continent of Asia into north and south regions that approximately correspond to temperate and tropical forests (Fig 1.). "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "GEDI04_A models are stratified by combinations of PFT derived from an infilled and error-corrected version MODIS data product MCD12Q1 V006 (Friedl et al., 2010, 2002). These are deciduous broadleaf trees (DBT; class 4), deciduous needleleaf trees (DNT; class 3), evergreen broadleaf trees (EBT, class 2), evergreen needleleaf trees (ENT, class 1), and grasses, shrubs, and woodlands (GSW, classes 5, 6, and 11; Fig. 1). "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2 Quality-control filters"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The FSBD is a living data archive that grows over time as new data sets are assimilated and improvements are made to existing records. The unfiltered database currently contains 31,414 simulated GEDI waveforms. After excluding incomplete projects and others that are inappropriate for GEDI (e.g., variable-radius plots), the unfiltered database contains 12,140 simulated GEDI waveforms. After applying quality-control filters, the database used to develop Version 1 of the GEDI04_A data product contains 8,587 simulated waveforms from 21 countries (Table 1). Below we indicate the number of simulated waveforms that were flagged by each quality-control filter. Because some waveforms were flagged by multiple filters, the total number of flagged waveforms does not sum to the 3,553 waveforms that were removed from the unfiltered FSBD."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.1 Incongruent AGBD and height"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "We excluded footprints when there was an incongruence between field-estimated AGBD and simulated RH98. In particular, when AGBD was < 1 Mg  ha"}, {"text": "-1", "superscript": true}, {"text": " and RH98 was > 5 m, the footprint was excluded (113 footprints, or 0.93% of the unfiltered database). When AGBD was > 150 Mg  ha"}, {"text": "-1", "superscript": true}, {"text": " and RH98 was < 5 m, the footprint was excluded (7 footprints, or 0.06%)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.2. Incongruent AGBD and canopy-cover fraction (CCF)"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "When CCF was 0 and RH98 > 5 m, the footprint was excluded (158 footprints, or 1.30%). The GEDI along-beam laser intensity half-width results in estimates of RH100 close to 4.5 m on surfaces of uniform reflectance with no elevation variation. One implication of this filter is that waveforms with 0 AGBD on sloped terrain were excluded from training data."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.3. Incongruent field-measured or modeled height and lidar height "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Some field data include measurements of individual tree height. When field measurements of height were not available, tree height was predicted using regional height-diameter allometric scaling equations. This is necessary because some allometric models used to predict individual tree mass ("}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": ") require tree height. When the difference between measured or predicted height and RH98 was > 10 m, we excluded the footprint (997 footprints, or 8.21%)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.4. Extrapolation of allometric scaling equations beyond measured range"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Some of the allometric scaling models used to predict "}, {"text": "M", "italic": true}, {"text": "i", "italic": true, "subscript": true}, {"text": " ", "italic": true}, {"text": "have a reported domain over which predictions are valid. These domains are defined by the data used to develop the equations ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "e5b19dda", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9227a11d", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "20d75c3a", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "ab059b12", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "734a16f4", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "; "}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "0b94e395", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). If a footprint contained at least one tree with a diameter, height, or wood specific gravity outside the range defined by the original authors, the footprint was excluded (640 footprints, or 5.27%)."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.5. Overlap between simulated footprints and field data"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Some simulated GEDI footprints are not completely contained within the boundaries of field-inventory plots. When this occurs, information about AGBD within the footprint is incomplete. Previous work has demonstrated that inclusion of these observations in statistical models causes relationships to be biased toward zero ("}, {"type": "ref", "refId": "9f38090e", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"text": "). If > 10% of the area of a simulated footprint was outside the boundaries of a field inventory plot, it was excluded from the FSBD (129 footprints, or 1.06%). "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.6. Large sample size"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "Data in the FSBD were contributed by numerous researchers without whom the development of comprehensive GEDI04_A models would not be possible. The data are organized into spatial units by project and then by plot. A project is single contribution from a given research group. For example, La Selva, Costa Rica and Robson Creek, Australia are individual projects. Some projects contain multiple plots. Because the number and size of plots is variable, a small number of large, stem-mapped plots contribute disproportionately to the total number of observations in the FSBD. Because these observations would overwhelm model fitting and evaluation at the expense of plots with fewer samples (and broader geographic coverage), we placed an upper limit of 200 footprints on the contribution of each plot (not project) to the analysis-ready data. When the number of footprints in a plot was < 200, we accepted all footprints that passed other filters. When the number of footprints in a plot was > 200 after applying other filters, we collected a stratified random sample of 200 footprints, where the per-footprint probability of inclusion was inversely proportional to the number of footprints in each of 20 equally spaced AGBD bins between the minimum and maximum AGBD in the plot, and probabilities were scaled so that each bin had an equal probability of contributing footprints to the sample."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.7. Stratification sample size, variable selection, and multicollinearity"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "We developed models for every combination of PFT and world region in Table 1 with > 50 footprints, and for every PFT and world region independently. For example, the model for EBT in the South America world region was developed using 3,441 footprints, and the global ENT model was developed using 1,986 footprints. We considered models with square-root or natural-logarithm transformations on the response and either the same transformation or no transformation on the predictors, for a total of four transformation scenarios. Candidate predictors were simulated RH metrics in increments of 10% and RH98 in addition to all possible two-way interactions. "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "We refer to combinations of PFT and world region as prediction strata. When there are training data to develop a model for a given prediction stratum, we use that model within the given combination of PFT and world region. However, there are 25 out of 35 prediction strata represented by < 50 footprints in the filtered GEDI FSBD. In these cases, we use the corresponding PFT model in 18 cases and an alternative model stratified by PFT and world region in 7 cases. These 7 cases represent two EBT strata, two DBT strata, and three DNT strata. "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "In the EBT prediction stratum within Europe and North America we use the corresponding DBT by world region models. We assume that models trained using data from DBT in the northern-latitude temperate zone will perform better in these prediction strata than models developed using EBT data. In the current version of the filtered FSBD, EBT samples are exclusively tropical or "}, {"text": "Eucalyptus", "italic": true}, {"text": ", and thus not representative of EBT in North America or Europe. In the DBT stratum within the South America world region and the country of Australia, we use the corresponding EBT model for the associated world region. In Australia, we assume the DBT classification is an error in MCD12Q1, because Australia lacks deciduous broadleaf forests. In the South America world region, DBT forests are likely to be tropical moist or dry forests that are similar to EBT of South America. Finally, we lack training data in DNT globally. We use a corresponding ENT by world region model for three of these strata (Australia, Europe, and North America). In the remaining DNT strata we lack a corresponding ENT by world region model and use the global ENT model."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "We computed all possible 1, 2, 3, and 4 variable predictor matrices. Two-way interactions were permitted in the absence of main effects. For example, we considered models that contained the interaction between RH50 and RH98, even when RH50 and RH98 were not included in the model as independent variables. We then eliminated predictor matrices that were multicollinear. We quantified multicollinearity by computing the Pearson correlation matrix for the candidate predictor matrix. If the maximum absolute value of the correlation coefficient was > 0.9, the candidate predictor matrix was excluded. We also computed the variance inflation factor (VIF). When VIF was > 10, the predictor matrix was excluded. For all candidates that passed both multicollinearity tests, we fit a weighted linear model by regressing the transformation of AGBD on the predictors. Weights were inversely proportional to the number of simulated footprints in each 5 degree grid cell used to quantify geographic transferability and scaled to sum to 1, so that training data in every grid cell contributed equally to the model, regardless of the number of observations within the grid cell."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "3.2.8. Benchmarking the candidate models"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The performance of all candidate models was evaluated by ranking every model in order of smallest mean residual error, smallest percentage root mean squared error, the maximum RH metric in the model, the number of coefficients in the model, and the number of RH metrics in the model. Mean residual error and RMSE were computed using geographically cross validated predictions, where mean residual error was: "}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "\\frac{1}{5} \\sum\\ _{j=1}^5 \\frac{1}{n_j} \\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n_j} Observed_{i,j}-Expected_{i,j}"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The interior sum is the mean within bin "}, {"text": "j", "italic": true}, {"text": ", where "}, {"text": "j ", "italic": true}, {"text": "is one of five quantile bins computed using predicted AGBD. Computing the mean residual error within quantile bins favors models that perform well across the range of AGBD. The percentage RMSE was computed according to:"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}, {"type": "equation", "children": [{"text": "RMSE = 100 \\times \\sqrt {\\frac{1}{n} \\sum\\ _{i=j}{n}(Observed_i-Expected_{i,j})^2} \\mathbin{/} \\frac{1}{n} \\sum\\ _{i=1}^{n}Observed_i"}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": "The model selection favors candidates that contain larger valued RH metrics over models with similar mean residual error and RMSE than models that contain smaller valued RH metrics. This is because RH metrics closer to the ground are more sensitive to differences between simulated and real GEDI waveforms than RH metrics higher in the canopy. Reducing simulator error for smaller valued RH metrics using the on-orbit transmit pulse shape and characteristics of recorded GEDI noise will be addressed in a subsequent version of GEDI04_A. Models with fewer coefficients and fewer RH metrics are preferred based on parsimony. The number of coefficients is not directly proportional to the number of RH metrics because candidate models contain interactions. For example, a model that contains the interaction between RH98 and RH50 as a single predictor contains two coefficients and two RH metrics. A model that contains only RH98 and RH50 as main effects contains three coefficients and two RH metrics."}]}, {"type": "p", "children": [{"text": ""}]}]}, "publication_references": [{"id": "859ca402", "isbn": "", "year": "2011", "issue": "", "pages": "177-189", "title": "Planted Forest Carbon Monitoring System - forest carbon model validation study for Pinus radiata", "series": "New Zealand Journal of Forestry Science", "volume": "", "authors": "Beets, P., N., Kimberley, M., O., Paul, T., S.H., Garrett, L., G.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "cbf9fe97", "isbn": "", "year": "", "issue": "", "pages": "2509-2512", "title": "Modeling laser altimeter return waveforms over complex vegetation using high-resolution elevation data", "series": "Geophys. Res. Lett.", "volume": "", "authors": "Blair, J.B., Hofton, M.A.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "cae3a97c", "isbn": "", "year": "2008", "issue": "", "pages": "38763890", "title": "Regional aboveground forest biomass using airborne and spaceborne LiDAR in Qubec", "series": "Remote Sensing of Environment", "volume": "112", "authors": "Boudreau, J., Nelson, R., Margolis, H., Beaudoin, A., Guindon, L., Kimes, D.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "30660e72", "isbn": "", "year": "1997", "issue": "", "pages": "", "title": "Estimating biomass and biomass change of tropical forests: a primer (FAO Forestry Paper", "series": "", "volume": "134", "authors": "Brown, S.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "ed685cd4", "isbn": "", "year": "2020", "issue": "", "pages": "112102", "title": "Terrestrial laser scanning in forest ecology: Expanding the horizon", "series": "Remote Sensing of Environment", "volume": "", "authors": "Calders, K., Adams, J., Armston, J., Bartholomeus, H., Bauwens, S., Bentley, L.P., Chave, J., Danson, F.M., Demol, M., Disney, M., Gaulton, R., Krishna Moorthy, S.M., Levick, S.R., Saarinen, N., Schaaf, C., Stovall, A., Terryn, L., Wilkes, P., Verbeeck, H.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "6fda62c4", "isbn": "", "year": "2007", "issue": "", "pages": "18866-18870", "title": "Contributions to accelerating atmospheric CO2 growth from economic activity, carbon intensity, and efficiency of natural sinks", "series": "PNAS", "volume": "104", "authors": "Canadell, J.G., Qur, C.L., Raupach, M.R., Field, C.B., Buitenhuis, E.T., Ciais, P., Conway, T.J., Gillett, N.P., Houghton, R.A., Marland, G.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "e5b19dda", "isbn": "", "year": "2014", "issue": "", "pages": "3177-3190", "title": "Improved allometric models to estimate the aboveground biomass of tropical trees", "series": "Global Change Biology", "volume": "20", "authors": "Chave, J., Rjou-Mchain, M., Brquez, A., Chidumayo, E., Colgan, M.S., Delitti, W.B.C., Duque, A., Eid, T., Fearnside, P.M., Goodman, R.C., Henry, M., Martnez-Yrzar, A., Mugasha, W.A., Muller-Landau, H.C., Mencuccini, M., Nelson, B.W., Ngomanda, A., Nogueira, E.M., Ortiz-Malavassi, E., Plissier, R., Ploton, P., Ryan, C.M., Saldarriaga, J.G., Vieilledent, G.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "b1166bee", "isbn": "", "year": "2012", "issue": "", "pages": "1191-1196", "title": "Tropical forest biomass estimation and the fallacy of misplaced concreteness", "series": "J Veg. Sci.", "volume": "23", "authors": "Clark, D.B., Kellner, J.R.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "5e8faa8f", "isbn": "", "year": "2000", "issue": "", "pages": "649-658", "title": "Quantifying the deciduousness of tropical forest canopies under varying climates", "series": "J. Veg. Sci.", "volume": "11", "authors": "Condit, R., Watts, K., Bohlman, S.A., Perez, R., Foster, R.B., Hubbell, S.P.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "9ab43f2d", "isbn": "", "year": "2007", "issue": "", "pages": "295-310", "title": "Estimating canopy structure of Douglas-fir forest stands from discrete-return LiDAR", "series": "Trees", "volume": "21", "authors": "Coops, N.C., Hilker, T., Wulder, M.A., St-Onge, B., Newnham, G., Siggins, A., Trofymow, J.A. (Tony)", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "9646918a", "isbn": "", "year": "2019", "issue": "", "pages": "275-281", "title": "Emergent Constraints on Climate-Carbon Cycle Feedbacks", "series": "Curr Clim Change Rep", "volume": "5", "authors": "Cox, P.M.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "ae033d7d", "isbn": "", "year": "2002", "issue": "", "pages": "", "title": "Estimation of tropical forest structural characteristics using large-footprint lidar", "series": "", "volume": "", "authors": "Drake, J., Dubayah, R., Clark, D.B., Knox, R.G., Hofton, M.A., Chazdon, R.L., Weishampel, J.F., Prince, S.D.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "95dd42c5", "isbn": "", "year": "2020a", "issue": "", "pages": "100002", "title": "The Global Ecosystem Dynamics Investigation: High-resolution laser ranging of the Earths forests and topography", "series": "Science of Remote Sensing", "volume": "1", "authors": "Dubayah, R., Blair, J.B., Goetz, S., Fatoyinbo, L., Hansen, M., Healey, S., Hofton, M., Hurtt, G., Kellner, J., Luthcke, S., Armston, J., Tang, H., Duncanson, L., Hancock, S., Jantz, P., Marselis, S., Patterson, P.L., Qi, W., Silva, C.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "594f393d", "isbn": "", "year": "2020b", "issue": "", "pages": "", "title": "GEDI L2A Elevation and Height Metrics Data Global Footprint Level V001", "series": "", "volume": "", "authors": "Dubayah, R., Hofton, M., Blair, J.B., Armston, J., Tang, H., Luthcke, S.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "04545783", "isbn": "", "year": "2021", "issue": "", "pages": "", "title": "GEDI L1B Geolocated Waveform Data Global Footprint Level V002", "series": "", "volume": "", "authors": "Dubayah, R., Luthcke, S., Blair, J., Hofton, M., Armston, J., Tang, H.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "65310eb2", "isbn": "", "year": "2010", "issue": "", "pages": "n/a-n/a", "title": "Estimation of tropical forest height and biomass dynamics using lidar remote sensing at La Selva, Costa Rica: FOREST DYNAMICS USING LIDAR", "series": "Journal of Geophysical Research: Biogeosciences ", "volume": "115", "authors": "Dubayah, R.O., Sheldon, S.L., Clark, D.B., Hofton, M.A., Blair, J.B., Hurtt, G.C., Chazdon, R.L.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "335cba16", "isbn": "", "year": "2017", "issue": "18", "pages": "", "title": "Implications of allometric model selection for county-level biomass mapping", "series": "", "volume": "12", "authors": "Duncanson, L., Huang, W., Johnson, K., Swatantran, A., McRoberts, R.E., Dubayah, R.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "592e2cb9", "isbn": "", "year": "2015", "issue": "", "pages": "1465-1475", "title": "Assessing the general patterns of forest structure: quantifying tree and forest allometric scaling relationships in the United States: Forest allometric variability in the United States", "series": "Global Ecology and Biogeography", "volume": "24", "authors": "Duncanson, L.I., Dubayah, R.O., Enquist, B.J.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "bc9bd3ba", "isbn": "", "year": "2013", "issue": "", "pages": "1617-1621", "title": "Urban Footprint ProcessorFully Automated Processing Chain Generating Settlement Masks From Global Data of the TanDEM-X Mission", "series": "IEEE Geoscience and Remote Sensing Letters", "volume": "10", "authors": "Esch, T., Marconcini, M., Felbier, A., Roth, A., Heldens, W., Huber, M., Schwinger, M., Taubenbck, H., Mller, A., Dech, S.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "80076a80", "isbn": "", "year": "2011", "issue": "", "pages": "1081-1106", "title": "Height-diameter allometry of tropical forest trees", "series": "", "volume": "8", "authors": "Feldpausch, T.R., Banin, L., Phillips, O.L., Baker, T.R., Lewis, S.L., Quesada, C.A., Affum-Baffoe, K., Arets, E.J.M.M., Berry, N.J., Bird, M., Brondizio, E.S., de Camargo, P., Chave, J., Djagbletey, G., Domingues, T.F., Drescher, M., Fearnside, P.M., Frana, M.B., Fyllas, N.M., Lopez-Gonzalez, G., Hladik, A., Higuchi, N., Hunter, M.O., Iida, Y., Salim, K.A., Kassim, A.R., Keller, M., Kemp, J., King, D.A., Lovett, J.C., Marimon, B.S., Marimon-Junior, B.H., Lenza, E., Marshall, A.R., Metcalfe, D.J., Mitchard, E.T.A., Moran, E.F., Nelson, B.W., Nilus, R., Nogueira, E.M., Palace, M., Patio, S., Peh, K.S.-H., Raventos, M.T., Reitsma, J.M., Saiz, G., Schrodt, F., Sonk, B., Taedoumg, H.E., Tan, S., White, L., Wll, H., Lloyd, J.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "1d395e1a", "isbn": "", "year": "1981", "issue": "", "pages": "281-289", "title": "Multiplicative Regression with Lognormal Errors", "series": "Forest Science", "volume": "27", "authors": "Flewelling, J.W., Pienaar, L.V.", "edition": "", "publisher": "", "publication_place": ""}, {"id": "112cbf78", "isbn": "", "year": "2003", "issue": "", "pages": "463-474", "title": "Predictive relations of tropical forest biomass from Landsat TM data and their transferability between regions", "series": "Remote Sensing of Environment", "volume": "85", "authors": "Foody, G.M., Boyd, D.S., Cutler, M.E